Sure, here is an example of how you can use WebClient in a reactive way to get API details from a PostgreSQL table, perform an HTTP request using those details, filter the response, and then save the result in a new table.

First, you will need to set up your project to use Spring WebFlux and R2DBC for reactive database access. You can do this by adding the following dependencies to your `pom.xml` file:

```xml
<dependencies>
  <dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-webflux</artifactId>
  </dependency>
  <dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-data-r2dbc</artifactId>
  </dependency>
  <dependency>
    <groupId>org.postgresql</groupId>
    <artifactId>r2dbc-postgresql</artifactId>
  </dependency>
</dependencies>
```

Next, you will need to create a `ConnectionFactory` bean to configure your database connection. Here is an example:

```java
@Configuration
public class DatabaseConfiguration {

  @Bean
  public ConnectionFactory connectionFactory() {
    return new PostgresqlConnectionFactory(
        PostgresqlConnectionConfiguration.builder()
            .host("localhost")
            .database("mydb")
            .username("myuser")
            .password("mypassword")
            .build());
  }
}
```

Now, you can create a `WebClient` bean to perform the HTTP request. Here is an example:

```java
@Configuration
public class WebClientConfiguration {

  @Bean
  public WebClient webClient(ReactiveConnectionFactory connectionFactory) {
    return WebClient.builder()
        .clientConnector(new ReactorClientHttpConnector(HttpClient.from(TcpClient.create(connectionFactory))))
        .build();
  }
}
```

Next, you can create a repository to get the API details from the PostgreSQL table. Here is an example:

```java
@Repository
public interface ApiRepository extends ReactiveCrudRepository<Api, Long> {
}
```

Now, you can create a service to perform the HTTP request and save the result in a new table. Here is an example:

```java
@Service
public class ApiService {

  private final ApiRepository apiRepository;
  private final WebClient webClient;
  private final R2dbcEntityTemplate r2dbcEntityTemplate;

  public ApiService(ApiRepository apiRepository, WebClient webClient, R2dbcEntityTemplate r2dbcEntityTemplate) {
    this.apiRepository = apiRepository;
    this.webClient = webClient;
    this.r2dbcEntityTemplate = r2dbcEntityTemplate;
  }

  public Flux<ApiResult> getApiResults() {
    return apiRepository.findAll()
        .flatMap(api -> webClient.get()
            .uri(api.getUrl())
            .header("Authorization", api.getAuthorization())
            .retrieve()
            .bodyToMono(ApiResponse.class)
            .filter(apiResponse -> apiResponse.getStatus() == 200)
            .map(apiResponse -> new ApiResult(api.getId(), apiResponse.getData())))
        .flatMap(apiResult -> r2dbcEntityTemplate.insert(apiResult));
  }
}
```

In this example, `Api` is a class that represents the API details from the PostgreSQL table, `ApiResponse` is a class that represents the response from the API, and `ApiResult` is a class that represents the filtered result that will be saved in the new table.

Finally, you can create a controller to expose the `getApiResults()` method as a REST endpoint. Here is an example:

```java
@RestController
public class ApiController {

  private final ApiService apiService;

  public ApiController(ApiService apiService) {
    this.apiService = apiService;
  }

  @GetMapping("/api-results")
  public Flux<ApiResult> getApiResults() {
    return apiService.getApiResults();
  }
}
```

