To run the API every 15 minutes starting from 00:00 till 23:45, you can use Spring's `@Scheduled` annotation in combination with a `Cron` expression.

Here is an example of how you can modify the `ApiController` class to run the `getApiResults()` method every 15 minutes according to the specified schedule:

```java
@RestController
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class ApiController {

  private final ApiService apiService;
  private final ApplicationEventPublisher eventPublisher;

  @Scheduled(cron = "0 0/15 0-23 * * *")
  public void getApiResults() {
    eventPublisher.publishEvent(new ApiResultsRequestedEvent());
  }

  @PostMapping("/api-results")
  public Flux<ApiResult> handleApiResultsRequestedEvent(@Eventually apiResultsRequestedEvent) {
    return apiService.getApiResults();
  }
}
```

In this example, the `@Scheduled` annotation is used to run the `getApiResults()` method every 15 minutes according to the `Cron` expression `0 0/15 0-23 * * *`. This expression means that the method will be called at the start of every hour, and then every 15 minutes thereafter until 23:59.

The `ApiResultsRequestedEvent` is a custom event that is published when the `getApiResults()` method is called. This event is then handled by the `handleApiResultsRequestedEvent()` method, which calls the `getApiResults()` method in the `ApiService` class.

To use the `@Scheduled` annotation, you will need to add the `spring-boot-starter-schedule` dependency to your `pom.xml` file:

```xml
<dependency>
  <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
  <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-schedule</artifactId>
</dependency>
```

