To run the API every 15 minutes starting from 00:00 till 23:45, store the data with additional fields for date and time, and send the data to a Kafka topic, you can modify the `ApiService` and `ApiController` classes as follows:

First, add the following dependencies to your `pom.xml` file:

```xml
<dependency>
  <groupId>org.springframework.kafka</groupId>
  <artifactId>spring-kafka</artifactId>
</dependency>
<dependency>
  <groupId>io.r2dbc</groupId>
  <artifactId>r2dbc-spi</artifactId>
</dependency>
```

Next, modify the `ApiService` class to include the additional fields for date and time, and to send the data to a Kafka topic:

```java
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class ApiService {

  private final ApiRepository apiRepository;
  private final WebClient webClient;
  private final R2dbcEntityTemplate r2dbcEntityTemplate;
  private final KafkaTemplate<String, ApiResult> kafkaTemplate;

  public Flux<ApiResult> getApiResults() {
    return apiRepository.findAll()
        .flatMap(api -> webClient.get()
            .uri(api.getUrl())
            .header("Authorization", api.getAuthorization())
            .retrieve()
            .bodyToMono(ApiResponse.class)
            .filter(apiResponse -> apiResponse.getStatus() == 200)
            .map(apiResponse -> {
              LocalDateTime now = LocalDateTime.now();
              ApiResult apiResult = new ApiResult(
                  api.getId(),
                  now.format(DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("yyyy-MM-dd")),
                  now.format(DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("HH:mm:ss")),
                  apiResponse.getData());
              kafkaTemplate.send("api-results", apiResult);
              return apiResult;
            }))
        .flatMap(apiResult -> r2dbcEntityTemplate.insert(apiResult));
  }
}
```

In this example, the `ApiResult` class has been modified to include additional fields for date and time. The `getApiResults()` method now formats the current date and time using the `DateTimeFormatter` class, and sets these values in the `ApiResult` object. The `KafkaTemplate` is then used to send the `ApiResult` object to a Kafka topic named "api-results".

Finally, modify the `ApiController` class to handle the custom event and to return the results from the `ApiService`:

```java
@RestController
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class ApiController {

  private final ApiService apiService;
  private final ApplicationEventPublisher eventPublisher;

  @Scheduled(cron = "0 0/15 0-23 * * *")
  public void getApiResults() {
    eventPublisher.publishEvent(new ApiResultsRequestedEvent());
  }

  @PostMapping("/api-results")
  public Flux<ApiResult> handleApiResultsRequestedEvent(@Eventually apiResultsRequestedEvent) {
    return apiService.getApiResults();
  }
}
```

In this example, the `handleApiResultsRequestedEvent()` method simply calls the `getApiResults()` method in the `ApiService` class and returns the results.

To use the `KafkaTemplate`, you will need to add the following configuration to your `application.yml` file:

```yaml
spring:
  kafka:
    bootstrap-servers: localhost:9092
    consumer:
      group-id: api-results-group
      auto-offset-reset: earliest
    producer:
      key-serializer: org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer
      value-serializer: org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer
```

This configuration specifies the Kafka bootstrap servers, consumer group ID, and serializers to use.

