To check if a computer is little endian or big endian using C++, you can use the following function:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

bool isLittleEndian() {
    int num = 1;
    char *ptr = (char *)&num;
    return (*ptr != 0);
}

int main() {
    if (isLittleEndian()) {
        std::cout << "The computer is little endian." << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "The computer is big endian." << std::endl;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

This function works by creating an integer variable `num` and setting it to 1. Then, it casts the address of `num` to a character pointer `ptr`. In a little endian system, the least significant byte is stored at the lowest address, so the first byte of `num` (pointed to by `ptr`) will be 1. In a big endian system, the most significant byte is stored at the lowest address, so the first byte of `num` will be 0. The function returns `true` if the first byte is not 0, indicating a little endian system.

Here's an alternative way to check for endianness using a union:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

bool isLittleEndian() {
    union {
        int num;
        char bytes[sizeof(int)];
    } endianTest;

    endianTest.num = 1;
    return endianTest.bytes[0] != 0;
}

int main() {
    if (isLittleEndian()) {
        std::cout << "The computer is little endian." << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "The computer is big endian." << std::endl;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

This function uses a union to overlay an integer variable and a character array of the same size. By setting the integer value to 1 and checking the first byte of the character array, you can determine the endianness of the system.

