Thymeleaf is a modern server-side Java template engine used for web applications. It's often used with Spring MVC to render HTML views. However, if you want to define your views without using Thymeleaf-specific tags, you can use plain HTML and Spring's Model-View-Controller (MVC) architecture.

Here's an example of how you can define a view using plain HTML and Spring MVC:

1. Create an HTML file for your view. This file should be placed in the `src/main/resources/templates` directory of your Spring Boot project. For example, you might create a file called `index.html` with the following content:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>My Web Application</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Welcome to my web application!</h1>
    <p>This is a plain HTML view without Thymeleaf tags.</p>
</body>
</html>
```

2. Configure your controller to return the view. In your controller, you can use the `ModelAndView` class to return the view along with any model data. For example:

```java
@Controller
public class HomeController {

    @GetMapping("/")
    public ModelAndView home() {
        ModelAndView modelAndView = new ModelAndView("index");
        modelAndView.addObject("message", "Hello, world!");
        return modelAndView;
    }
}
```

In this example, the `home()` method returns the `index.html` view and adds a model attribute called `message` with the value "Hello, world!".

3. Access the view in your browser. When you access the root URL of your application (e.g., `http://localhost:8080/`), you should see the plain HTML view rendered in your browser.

Note that this approach doesn't take advantage of Thymeleaf's features, such as template inheritance, layout dialects, or integration with Spring's data binding. If you need these features, you might want to consider using Thymeleaf or another template engine that supports them.

