Here's a simple JavaScript function that will only run once, using a flag variable to keep track of its execution status:

```javascript
let hasRun = false;

function runOnce() {
  if (!hasRun) {
    hasRun = true;
    // Your code here
    console.log("Function ran once.");
  }
}

// Testing the function
runOnce(); // Outputs: Function ran once.
runOnce(); // No output, as the function has already run once.
```

Alternatively, you can use the `once` property of the `EventTarget` interface, which is available in most modern browsers:

```javascript
function runOnce() {
  // Your code here
  console.log("Function ran once.");
}

const eventTarget = new EventTarget();

eventTarget.addEventListener("runOnce", runOnce, { once: true });

// Dispatching the event
eventTarget.dispatchEvent(new Event("runOnce"));

// Trying to run the function again
eventTarget.dispatchEvent(new Event("runOnce")); // No output, as the event listener has been removed.
```

In this example, the `runOnce` function will only be called once when the "runOnce" event is dispatched, and the event listener will be automatically removed after the first invocation.

