In this example, the `once` higher-order function takes a function `fn` as an argument and returns a new function that wraps `fn`. The new function keeps track of whether `fn` has been executed using the `executed` flag. If `fn` hasn't been executed yet, the new function calls `fn` and sets the `executed` flag to `true`. If `fn` has already been executed, the new function does nothing.

You can use this `once` higher-order function to create new functions that will only run once, like `greetOnce` in the example above.

