The `git stash apply` command re-applies the changes that were stashed using `git stash save`. When you run `git stash save`, Git takes the changes in your working directory and index (staged changes) and saves them on a stack of stashes. The command also clears your working directory and index, effectively reverting them to the state of the last commit.

When you later run `git stash apply`, Git takes the most recently stashed changes from the top of the stash stack and re-applies them to your working directory and index. This means that the changes are brought back to your working directory, but they are not automatically committed.

If you want to keep the stashed changes after applying them, you can simply run `git stash apply` without any additional commands. However, if you want to remove the stashed changes after applying them, you can run `git stash drop` immediately after `git stash apply`. This will remove the most recently applied stash from the stack.

In the context of the Gradle task, the `doLast` block applies the stashed changes and optionally drops them. This means that after the tests are run, the changes that were stashed before checking out the `origin/master` branch are re-applied to the working directory. If you want to keep the stashed changes, you can remove the line that calls `git stash drop`.

Here's the relevant part of the task:

```groovy
doLast {
    // Apply the stashed changes
    exec {
        commandLine 'git', 'stash', 'apply'
    }

    // Drop the stashed changes (optional, if you want to keep them, remove this line)
    exec {
        commandLine 'git', 'stash', 'drop'
    }
}
```

By running this task, you can test your code against the `origin/master` branch and then restore your changes after the tests are complete.

